        <h1 class="pg-title">Juno</h1>
        <p class="pg-subtitle">Roman queen of the gods, patroness of marriage, women, and Rome itself</p>
      </header>

      <p>
        The month of June on the Gregorian calendar honors the queen of the Roman gods. Her name was <strong>Juno</strong> (Greek <em>Hera</em>), and she was the wife of Jupiter, the protectress of Rome, and the goddess most directly associated with marriage, childbirth, and the lives of women.
      </p>

      <h2>Who She Was</h2>

      <p>
        Juno was Rome's queen-of-the-gods. She was Jupiter's wife and sister, and she ruled at his side. The Greeks knew her as Hera — a goddess famous in mythology for jealousy, vindictiveness, and the punishment of her husband's many lovers. The Romans softened her character somewhat and elevated her function: Juno was the patroness of women, of marriage covenants, of childbirth, and most especially of the city of Rome itself.
      </p>

      <p>
        Her temples were among the most important in Rome. She was worshiped under several names — <em>Juno Regina</em> (queen), <em>Juno Lucina</em> (goddess of childbirth), <em>Juno Moneta</em> (the goddess from whose temple Rome's coins were minted, and from whose name we get the English word <em>money</em>). Roman matrons dedicated their lives to her, and brides offered her sacrifices on their wedding days.
      </p>

      <p>
        The month of June was sacred to her. Romans believed it was the most fortunate month for marriage — a wedding in June would be blessed by the queen of the gods. The tradition of "June weddings" that persists in Western culture comes directly from Juno's patronage. Latin <em>Iunius</em>, the month of Juno, became June.
      </p>

      <h2>Why It Matters</h2>

      <p>
        Marriage and childbirth are gifts from Yahuah, not from Juno. The Father designed marriage in the garden when He brought Eve to Adam. He blessed childbirth from the very first command — to be fruitful and multiply. He needs no help from a Roman queen-goddess to bless His people's marriages or to sustain their families.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Genesis 2:24</span> — "Therefore shall a man leave his father and his mother, and shall cleave unto his wife: and they shall be one flesh."
      </div>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Psalm 127:3</span> — "Lo, children are an heritage of Yahuah: and the fruit of the womb is his reward."
      </div>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Proverbs 18:22</span> — "Whoso findeth a wife findeth a good thing, and obtaineth favour of Yahuah."
      </div>

      <p>
        The pagan world wanted a queen-goddess to oversee marriages and childbirth because they did not know the Father who designed both. Yahuah's people did know Him. Marriages and births under His covenant were never under Juno's care. To name a month after her — and to keep "June weddings" as a cultural tradition — preserves the old pagan instinct that something else needs to bless what Yahuah has already blessed.
      </p>

      <h2>Two Clocks That Cannot Be Mixed</h2>

      <p>
        Some will ask: <em>"What month in Yahuah's calendar is June really?"</em> The question itself is the mistake.
      </p>

      <p>
        Yahuah's months are counted from the new moon. The first month — Aviv — begins when Spica meets the moon at the new moon nearest the spring equinox. Every month after that begins the day after the visible new-moon sliver appears. The months are numbered. <strong>Their start dates do not line up with the Roman months — and they shift slightly from one year to the next.</strong>
      </p>

      <p>
        What we call "June" on the Roman calendar will overlap with parts of two different months on Yahuah's calendar — and which two depends on the year. To say "June is really Month X" is to commit the same error as saying "Christ died on Friday." It mixes Babylon's clock with Yahuah's clock, when the two were never meant to translate into each other.
      </p>

      <h2>What to Do With It</h2>

      <p>
        The sixth month of the modern calendar is named after the queen of the Roman gods. The wedding industry built around "June weddings" is downstream of pagan tradition — Roman brides offered sacrifices to Juno and believed her blessing made June the luckiest month for marriage. Most who plan their weddings in June today have no idea. But the cultural memory is intact, and the name on the calendar still carries it forward.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Yahuah's clock and Babylon's clock are not the same clock.</strong> His months are counted from the new moon He set in the firmament — not from a Roman queen-goddess of marriage. The faithful watch the heavens and let the new moon tell them when a month has begun. The two answers are as far apart as east is from west.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-pull">
        June is Juno's month. The marriages of Yahuah's people are blessed by Him alone. No queen-goddess oversees their vows, and no Roman festival adds anything to a covenant the Father Himself designed.
      </div>

